Look for any `error` messages that might help you to identify the problem.

Add the following code to `onCreate()` in `SearchContantActivity`

    Log.d(&quot;SearchContactActivity&quot;, &quot;onCreate called&quot;);

2. Make sure the columns are correct

Check the column names in `SQL`, match them to `database` and make the `Java` code match it also.

Retrieve the value of a column named for example `DATA_NOPOL`.

    int nopolIndex = cursor.getColumnIndex(&quot;DATA_NOPOL&quot;);
    String nopol = cursor.getString(nopolIndex);

`getColumnIndex()` returns the index, `getString()` retrieves the value.

3. Check the number of `columns` returned:

The number of `columns` returned have to match the number of `columns` that you get in the code.

Use `getColumnCount()`:

    int columnCount = cursor.getColumnCount();
    Log.d(&quot;SearchContactActivity&quot;, &quot;Column count: &quot; + columnCount);

4. Check `columns` `data` type

The `data` types returned by `SQL` has to match the `data` of the vars in the code.

Check the `data` using `getType()`

    int nopolIndex = cursor.getColumnIndex(&quot;DATA_NOPOL&quot;);
    int nopolType = cursor.getType(nopolIndex);
