Sadly this is not how Java&#39;s exceptions work.


NumberFormatException occurs only when your try statement throws a relevant exception.

Over here in your case.  e != null or e==null these checks are unnecessary due to the fact that once an exception is thrown those are bound to be not null.

Instead what you should be doing is as follows:

    String o = &quot;&quot;;
    try {
    // all the sanity checks will be here.
    if (o==null) {
      console.log(&quot;o is null&quot;);
    }
    
    // your processing of valid number.

    }catch(java.lang.NumberFormatException e) {
    //invalid input is found
    console.log(&quot;Incorrect input of o: &quot; + e);
    }

