In XML, any character can be encoded using its Unicode code-point, as a so-called [&quot;character entity reference&quot;][1] using a syntax like this:

```xml
&lt;TextView xmlns:android=&quot;http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android&quot;
    android:textColor=&quot;#000000&quot;
    android:layout_width=&quot;wrap_content&quot;
    android:layout_height=&quot;wrap_content&quot;
    android:text=&quot;&amp;#x1F600;&quot;
    android:textSize=&quot;48sp&quot; /&gt;
```

The initial `&amp;` character introduces the entity reference, and the trailing `;` terminates it. The `#` indicates that the reference is a _numeric_ reference (as opposed to referring to an entity by name), and the `x` indicates that the number is in hexadecimal. The `1F600` is the Unicode codepoint.

NB Java and JavaScript use the `\` character as an escape mechanism but in XML, as in HTML, it has no special meaning; a `\` just signifies a `\`.

  [1]: https://www.w3.org/TR/xml11/#sec-references

